notesStmt.note: This illuminated and illustrated Arabic manuscript of the Gospels by Matthew (Mattá), Mark (Marquṣ), Luke (Lūqā), and John (Yūḥannā) was copied in Egypt by Ilyās Bāsim Khūrī Bazzī Rāhib, who was most likely a Coptic monk, in Anno Mundi 7192 / 1684 CE. The text is written in naskh in black ink with rubrics in red. The decoration is comprised of illuminated headpieces, numerous floral paintings, and approximately fifty illustrations (fols. 3a, 8a, 10a, 18a, 20b, 23a, 24a, 25a, 31b, 39a, 41a, 43a, 47a, 48b, 58a, 74a, 81b, 85b, 86b, 88b, 89b, 131b, 134b, 137b, 138b, 143b, 151a, 157a, 161a, 166a, 169a, 188b, 190b, 192b, 196a, 201a, 204b, 207a, 208b, 212a, 215a, 219a, 223b, 231a, 234a, 240b, 244a, 245a, 254b, and 260a ). The brown goatskin binding with blind-tooled central oval medallion, pendants, and cornerpieces is contemporary with the manuscript.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Arabic.

msItem.title: Anājīl
اناجيل
msItem.incipit: مقدمة انجيل متى اللذي هذانا بتوفيقه...
msItem.note: Contains the four Gospels by Matthew (Mattá), Mark (Marquṣ), Luke (Lūqā), and John (Yūḥannā); each Gospel introduced by a short preface

colophon.note: ʿallaqahu bi-yadih al-fāniyah afqar ʿibād Allāh taʿālá Ilyās Bāsim Khūrī Bazzī Rāhib sanat 7192 li-Ādam /1/ [underneath by a later hand] al-muwāfiq sanah 1684 masīḥīyah
Contains the name of the scribe and the date of copying, which is given in Anno Mundi (li-Ādam)

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in green and yellow

handDesc.handNote: Written in naskh with headserifs (influenced by tawqīʿ) in black ink and rubrics in red ink

decoDesc.decoNote: Headpieces; illustrations; floral designs; text frames in green and yellow

binding.p: Contemporary with manuscript; brown goatskin (with flap); blind-tooled central oval medallion and cornerpieces
